                <div class="col-sm-6">
                    <h3>Earth, in its earlier state, was a pristine paradise of untouched landscapes and thriving ecosystems. Vast, dense forests stretched across continents, rich in biodiversity, providing habitats for countless species. Rivers ran crystal clear, free from pollution, nourishing fertile lands. The air was pure, carrying the scent of flowers and forests, and the skies were free from industrial smog, revealing brilliant blue expanses by day and star-filled nights. 
                    </h3>
                    <h3>Oceans teemed with marine life, from the shallow coral reefs to the deep blue depths, while polar ice caps remained vast and undisturbed, regulating the climate. The balance between Earth’s systems—its atmosphere, water cycles, and ecosystems—was harmonious, creating a stable environment where natural processes flourished. Early human civilizations lived in sync with nature, relying on its abundance while leaving minimal impact on the planet. This untouched beauty was a testament to Earth's innate ability to support life, providing the foundation for the diversity and richness we know today.
                    </h3>
                </div>
