                <div class="col-sm-6">
                    <h3>In the past, Earth was a masterpiece of natural beauty, shaped over millions of years by geological forces, evolution, and the delicate balance of its ecosystems. Lush rainforests, such as the Amazon and the Congo, were expansive and teemed with diverse species, many of which remain undiscovered to this day. These forests acted as the planet's lungs, absorbing carbon dioxide and releasing oxygen, maintaining a climate that supported a vast array of life. Mountain ranges, carved by the slow movement of tectonic plates, stood tall and untouched, their snow-capped peaks shimmering under the sun, while sprawling savannas and grasslands hosted herds of wildlife that roamed freely across the plains.</h3>
                    <h3>The oceans, covering over 70% of the Earth's surface, were once thriving nurseries of marine life, home to coral reefs so vibrant they were known as the rainforests of the sea. Coastal areas, free from human development, were pristine, with mangroves and wetlands serving as natural buffers against storms and providing breeding grounds for countless species. Rivers flowed freely, unencumbered by dams or pollution, carving valleys and shaping landscapes in their natural course. Glaciers in the polar regions and on mountaintops were vast and stable, reflecting sunlight and regulating global temperatures through the ice-albedo effect.
                    </h3>
